            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"> Advanced Decks</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">Eidon Splooge - The Best Version</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size=1>(4.46)</font> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=21809">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8889">Jim "Jim Wong" Wong</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=8889&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> This deck is just another one of the Eidon Splooge Naroom stereotypes, but this time, its the best version available! ;)</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> February 27, 2002</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Magi: <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(410)">Evu</a> (<a href="javascript:card_browser(403)">Plith</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(400)">Furok</a>, and <a href="javascript:card_browser(428)">Vortex of Knowledge</a>) <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(414)">Tryn</a> (<a href="javascript:card_browser(423)">Grow</a> and <a href="javascript:card_browser(404)">Rudwot</a>) <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(515)">Eidon</a> (<a href="javascript:card_browser(603)">Forest Jile</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(423)">Grow</a>, and <a href="javascript:card_browser(400)">Furok</a>) <br>
<br>
Creatures(24/25): <br>
1x <a href="javascript:card_browser(403)">Plith</a> <br>
1x <a href="javascript:card_browser(409)">Weebo</a> <br>
1x <a href="javascript:card_browser(400)">Furok</a><br>
1x <a href="javascript:card_browser(404)">Rudwot</a>***<br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(405)">Stagadan</a> <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(603)">Forest Jile</a> <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(761}<a href="javascript:card_browser({842)">Bungaloo</a></a> <br>
3x <a href="javascript:card_browser(399)">Eebit</a> <br>
3x <a href="javascript:card_browser(407)">Twee</a> <br>
3x <a href="javascript:card_browser(401}<a href="javascript:card_browser({516)">Gia</a>nt <a href="javascript:card_browser(398)">Carillion</a></a> <br>
3x <a href="javascript:card_browser(607)">Wasperine</a> <br>
3x <a href="javascript:card_browser(606)">Tree Hinko</a> <br>
<br>
Spells(6): <br>
1x <a href="javascript:card_browser(428)">Vortex of Knowledge</a> <br>
1x <a href="javascript:card_browser(423)">Grow</a> <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(498)">Thunderquake</a> <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(355)">Shockwave</a> <br>
<br>
Relics(11): <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(507)">Relic Stalker</a> <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(652)">Rayje&#39;s Belt</a> <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(418)">Energy Band</a> <br>
2x <a href="javascript:card_browser(421)">Robe of Vines</a> <br>
3x <a href="javascript:card_browser(512)">Warrior&#39;s Boots</a> <br>
<br>
*** - Optional and for metagaming purposes, if you think you need another creature, then put it in, otherwise don&#39;t.   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> NO DREAM&#39;S END AND IT STILL BEATS TYLER MAYS! <br>
<br>
Amazing isn&#39;t it? Well in all honesty, there doesn&#39;t even need to be any DE cards in this deck, save Zannah (but thats straying away from the deck archtype). Here follows the pretty much indepth strategy: <br>
<br>
1st Magi: Evu <br>
<br>
Evu, my friends, is the beast of a starter Magi. He and Tiller are the starters for Naroom and both can do an exceptionally good job (but its your choice whether or not you want to use Tiller or Evu). In any case, Evu can draw 3 cards instead of his normal 2 per turn thanks to his Power/Effect, which is a great benefit when it comes down to it. Now, when you start with him, you always want to go first and fetch the Plith, Vortex of Knowledge and Furok. Draw up to 5, use the Vortex and this is where the strategy differs on your opponent. If you know that your opponent stands a strong chance against you, put out your bigger creatures and try to keep Evu with a decent amount of energy (as to keep him alive if all your creatures die). If you think you have a great chance of beating your opponent (and he doesn&#39;t play Underneath), then go all out and play Evu to his max, you&#39;ll get your entire deck into your hand soon if you can survive for long enough. In any case, always remember to start ou by playing the Plith and Furok to keep a good defense and add on a creature above that so your opponent can&#39;t one turn KO you. Also, make sure to put out a Robe of Vines as soon as possible as goes the same for an Energy Band if you&#39;re wanting to win with Evu. <br>
<br>
Anyway, after your first turn, you want to think whether or not you want to save up cards for Eidon or beat your opponent without even have to switch to him (most times). If you save up cards, then you also want to play your stronger creatures and keep Evu alive as long as possible, otherwise vice versa with the exception of not keeping Evu alive. ;) <br>
<br>
After Evu finally dies (if he even does), you go to the almighty Tryn. Fetch Grow, Rudwot (optional) and start. Tryn here is also quite the beast of a Magi, a free 2 energy to any of your creatures whenever you want it (sorta). In any case, playing Tryn is also quite different here. If you&#39;re trying to stall for Eidon to massacre your opponent with weenies, then you have to play THE big creatures, which means the Giant Carillions and whatever else to stall your opponent even more. Weebos and your GCs are good fun, especially when your Weebo doesn&#39;t die with a recharge (thanks to Refresh). Anyway, if you go with the Keep Evu Alive to Win strategy, don&#39;t play any Energy Bands or Robe of Vines, you&#39;ll want to save them for Eidon, UNLESS you absolutely know you can beat your opponent. <br>
<br>
Tryn will often last for a looooong time, (I&#39;ve had up to 50 energy on her at once), and because of this, you have to keep on playing the large creatures and save the little mini-duplicate ones for Eidon. Once again, your entire strategy almost differs now on Ormagon or Xyx Elders, both are deadly to your weenie hoards. If your opponent does play his devestating creatures, still save for Eidon, but remember to keep it to a limit when you&#39;re playing with him. And now, without any further ado, to Eidon himself. Beast of Beasts. <br>
<br>
Eidon! He&#39;s magical, he&#39;s great, he&#39;s one hecka energy saver. With his Effect, you can play 3 Eebits, 3 Bungaloos, 3 Tree Hinkos, and 3 Twees for only 6 ENERGY! This is a great way to storm your opponent and wipe the off the board. However, nowadays, since there isn&#39;t any way of preventing an Ormagon from coming around to beat you up, you have to limit your attack. For instance, just play a couple of creatures when he first flips and keep it to a minimum (but with hard hitting creatures as well like Wasperines). A Robe of Vines is most definitely needed along with an Energy Band. In any case, if you&#39;ve been saving up a ton and you know your opponent can&#39;t hurt you, play to your heart&#39;s desire and literally make them cry. :D <br>
<br>
Finally, have Eidon hold out for a long time as well (thanks to Hinkos too), and you should be able to finally win if you play right (and not wrong, duh. :) ) <br>
<br>
One important thing about Eidon, he was mostly broken before the Belt Errata, and now he&#39;s just a really powerful Magi, but you must remember to NOT totally put out your hand once your reach him. You have to control him, in other words you gotta mix and match cards. For instance, use Shockwaves or TQs and put out a few creatures so Eidon is sitting at around 6 energy each turn. This is probably the best benefit of energy you get from him, and if a disastrous creature does arrive, then just plop out some more creatures and be glad you saved them. <br>
<br>
Relics and Spells overview: <br>
<br>
Robe of Vines: Adds one to all your Naroom creatures when they&#39;re played. Very fun with Eidon Splooge here, especially with Eidon (dur). Evu is also a good subject to use it on, but the true power of the Robe comes when Eidon flips and lays down the law. Save one for Eidon and decide yourself when to play the other one (either for Evu or Tryn) <br>
<br>
Rayje&#39;s Belt: What can I say? Its still a great card, but it can&#39;t stop an Ormagon now unfortunately. For the Belt to work the best, don&#39;t play it unless you see a card you need to Lockdown, and then play it (since your Relics, Spells, Powers and Effects are first each turn). Don&#39;t worry too much about a Stalked Belt, its not a total staple to keep this deck going. <br>
<br>
Energy Band: Another goody fun relic to use with Tryn or Evu. With Tryn, she can now add 4 energy to any creature for only 1 off of her, and its fun for a GC Stomp Attack combo (with a Weebo replenishment). For Evu, its good for those times when your Hinko needs some power and takes a little energy off a Magi, perhaps. No definite need to save one for Eidon, but its handy nontheless. <br>
<br>
Warrior&#39;s Boots: Ahh, what a fun thing to use, basically, you don&#39;t really need it for Eidon too much (since your opponent can&#39;t concentrate on about 10 creatures at once), but they&#39;re good for a short attack, especially when you can kill the opposing Magi by Bootsing out a GC, stomping, Refreshing, then killing them. In any case, use these sparingly, and don&#39;t necessarily waste them on a Weebo unless you really need to. <br>
<br>
Spells: <br>
<br>
Vortex of Knowledge: Its a good one-use thing, if you go first, always grab it and use it, it ends up as a 1 card advantage for you. However, if you do end up drawing this card halfway through the game, don&#39;t just put it at the back of your hand, use it if you need to get some cards and I wouldn&#39;t worry about your opponent either. <br>
<br>
Grow: Dice-spinning fun! Be sure to use it when you grab it with Tryn since Eidon will just be picking it right back up later on. In any case, don&#39;t really think of it as a great way to gain energy since it all depends on a die roll, but use it as sort of a last minute resort to get your GC back up to one final stomp, or an overpowered Tree Hinko. <br>
<br>
Thunderquake: Ka-boom, this is really really really fun to use when you flip over Eidon, lay down the creatures, then just wipe your opponents board since Eidon is left with so much energy. Its a good way to get rid of those annoying Flutter Yups, or even the occasional Naroom Swarm deck you go against. In any case, don&#39;t bother to use it with Evu since his Energize isn&#39;t that great, but its good for a 1st turn deal when you flip a new Magi. <br>
<br>
Shockwave: Wowee-zowee, this IS the epitomy of a cool card (with the exception of the Tree Hinko). Get rid of those bothersome super Core cards or just any other big creature (goodbye Voda and KT), and although it is a tad bit costy, its essentially a Giant Carillion bottled up into a spell. Use it sparingly again, and usually only with Tryn or Eidon. <br>
<br>
Well, thats mostly it for this deck. It takes some time to learn how to play correctly, so test it out with your friends a lot or just play in tournaments. I promise you&#39;ll do very well. <br>
<br>
